<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">The question that drives the whole unit: <em>What does a planet need to support life?</em></p>
  <p>Today we open Unit 1 by zooming all the way out. Before we define habitability, before we name conditions, before we touch any vocabulary — we look. Four planets, no labels. You decide which could support life and how you'd know.</p>
  <p><strong>Carry-forward from Unit 0:</strong> remember <a href="/units/unit-0/block-2/">Lovelock (1965)</a> from Unit 0 Blocks 2 + 3 — the paper that proposed detecting life by reading a planet's atmosphere for chemical disequilibrium? Meeting it again here isn't a coincidence. "How would we recognise life elsewhere?" is the same question as "what makes a planet habitable?", asked from the other side. The modern follow-up you previewed, Thompson et al. (2022), is literally about TRAPPIST-1e — one of the planets in today's image set. Today's launch isn't a new framework — it's the same OPVL muscle you built in U0, applied to a new question. You'll work with new sources this unit (NASA archive entries, peer-reviewed astronomy papers, AI explanations of habitability), and Lovelock + Thompson return when you build your habitability framework. Every U1 source gets OPVL'd the same way you OPVL'd Lovelock in U0.</p>
  <p>The point of today isn't to be right. It's to surface what you already believe — and the gaps in what you know. Whatever five factors you list at the end of class become the seed of the framework you'll build, test, and defend over the next ten blocks.</p>
  <p>By Block 10 you'll deliver the <a href="/units/unit-1/assessment-goldilocks-report/">Goldilocks Report</a>: a structured comparison of Earth, Mars, and a chosen exoplanet against your own habitability criteria, defended to peers playing a NASA evaluation committee. That's where this question goes. Today is where it starts.</p>
</section>

